  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law intersects with national laws on money laundering through several key mechanisms:\n\n1. Global Regulatory Frameworks\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- International standards for combating financial crimes\n\n2. Cooperative Enforcement Mechanisms\n- Mutual legal assistance treaties\n- Information sharing between financial intelligence units\n- Extradition agreements for financial crimes\n- Cross-border investigation collaborations\n\n3. Compliance Requirements\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- Enhanced due diligence for high-risk jurisdictions\n- Standardized reporting protocols\n\n4. Legal Harmonization\n- Consistent definitions of money laundering\n- Similar legal standards for investigating financial crimes\n- Coordinated approaches to asset seizure and recovery\n- Alignment of legal definitions across jurisdictions\n\n5. Sanctions and Penalties\n- International economic sanctions\n- Asset freezing mechanisms\n- Coordinated financial restrictions\n- Diplomatic and economic pressure on non-compliant jurisdictions\n\nThese intersections create a complex, multilayered approach to preventing and prosecuting money laundering globally.",
